‘Thy small but faithful offerings, Phidyle, will save thy crops and flock33 thou needest not be anxious that thou hast no great victim. Pure hands, a little salt and meal, is all thy guardian gods require.'

Thus Horace reassures a country housewife, and shows that, for all his lack of saith in the state religion, he was not without sympathy with the beliefs of the common folk. Read Lang, Letters to Dead Authom,
